				<cite class="fn">BladeMcCool</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>

		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://www.loper-os.org/?p=1009&amp;cpage=1#comment-3709">October 19, 2012 at 6:25 pm</a></div>

		<p>The fact that you compare this to the tulip bubble implies you don&#8217;t have a good grasp on supply and demand ecomonics. I re-iterate there will only ever be 21 million bitcoins while there can be an infinite number of tulips or federal reserve notes. As long as bitcoin miners are still dedicating hashpower to put transactions in blocks, bitcoin will continue to have its intrinsic value of signed title transfers of accounting units. Which as you&#8217;ll note was the only value bitcoins had before someone bought a pizza with them. And if they still have an intrinsic value of signed title transfer abilty, then I&#8217;m not the only one who will want to own the entire supply, and thus I&#8217;ll be in a bidding war with at least one other person for the entire supply of Bitcoins.</p>

		<div class="reply">
		<a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/?p=1009&#038;buffer_share=3c2a6&#038;replytocom=3709#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-3709", "3709", "respond", "1009")'>Reply</a>		</div>
